interactions.feelings: Well, here we continue about this Pastille. This colour is absolutely magnificent to me, I can't tell whether this picture reproduces its colour correctly, but hopefully it does, the correct colour of the chair, and it, and I like that colour and then I like the asymmetry in it, that’s probably partly because of the angle of view. This is somehow, doesn’t this, doesn’t this rock somehow, nicely, so that it’s like rockable. With this chair, rocking is allowed.

And now when I look at it with today's eyes, I see in it a pretty beautifully crafted object, which is, which has a lot of such features that are not, that attach it to the design of the 1950s and 1960s. It has clear features, the chosen material is of high quality and, and this design. It is made of durable, strong metal. The colors have been carefully chosen, it has blue and white, Finnish colors, and then a little bit of red has been put in.

interactions.feelings: That is by no means a grandma cup to me, since it was like my parents' normal coffee cup. And they had some that were brown-edged, and then later purchased some that were gold-edged. And now, of course, I have them in the cupboard, but I don’t use the ones with flowers on them. But I have a lot of them as a white version. And its goodness is based on the fact, that coffee tastes better when drunk from a cup with a thin edge, than when drunk from a mug. And then the handle is terribly good to hold in your hand. So, it is kind of like ergonomic, whether you like the form of it or not. But yes, it works well as a coffee cup.

interactions.feelings: Once at the cabin we came up with a game where we guessed different things, to spend time. Myself, I tried to make the others guess the name of the Iris factory. "Violet, a spring garden flower, impressive, a typical motif in 20th-century decorations." The boys were obviously not gardening people, as they found it difficult to guess it. And the funniest guess was the baboon flower!

interactions.feelings: And what's special about this, is this wooden handle that can be used to lift the cover comfortably. One won’t, one won’t burn their fingers. This iron pot in the picture is red. Here it is enamelled white on the inside. It probably doesn’t interfere with the functionality of the pot, but I personally like that original black iron pot. And as I’ve said before, it’s absolutely wonderful compared to a regular frying pan. It doesn’t spill the fats because it has high edges. But every time I use my own pot, I have used it many times this year, too, always, immediately after use, I wash it with hot water and a dish brush, by no means soap. With hot water and a brush, and then I put oil on it right away. And because of that, it's always in good condition.

interactions.feelings: I'm Marke, and I chose a rug like this. And I checked from behind there, and saw that it is made by Ritva Puotila, from The Friends of Finnish Handicraft. When my parents died, they had ordered a big blue rug from her, which of course no one wanted to take. And then I took it to The Finnish White Ribbon Union. And they fell in love with it, one could see that. And they took it to the laundry. And there it is, hangs on their wall.

Then my aunt died, and she also had two rugs. Then no one wanted those either, because nowadays the apartments are so low, and they require a higher, three, four meter apartment. And then I took it there again, to the Finnish White Ribbon Union on Liisankatu. There they hang, washed and beautiful. But rugs don’t really fit into these modern apartments.

interactions.feelings: And then there is this pot. Here it was... Here it is now... I didn't have that one either, but like a normal iron pot. But I remember it very well, I used this one a lot. That, too, can be somewhere. That one was also red. These are both red.

So at the moment, I have here. These Savonia cutlery by Sorsakoski are used at home. They are probably of new production, they are very light and slender. Those that there were before, were they now by Hackman or what, the ones with stripes, they were also from the 1960s. Of those I have the whole series.

And one always got these as a wedding present. Getting married in your twenties, so the table of presents was full of this kind of supplies. I’m not quite certain if all of the ones I have were wedding presents, but I think almost all of them were. There are the Fiskars scissors. Then later came this Aalto vase. I have a small one. And then there are these Myrna cups. And in general, I collect, I’m like this, I go to flea markets and I love everything old like this. And well, the house is full. So the children are worried about where we’ll end up with all that stuff. Well, the recycling centres do come and take it.

interactions.feelings: I myself have a rug woven by my late mother, “Muisto Karjalasta”. By Norma Heimola. It was made in the 1970s. And she had this situation in the 1950s, after being evacuated, that with the wives of her uncles, they used this kind of material, dismantled felt from a paper machine. The felt from the paper machine was dismantled into yarn and dyed with dyes from plants. So this rug I now have in my archives, I’m wondering where should one put it. It dates from 1952, 1953. And its model is “Itämaan tietäjät”, or something like that, you can find it in the rug catalogs. And how skilfully these women have made decorations and embellishments for themselves, then after the war.

You will not take one? Well, for me, the Pastille chair. It’s Eero's chair, from the 1960s. And at some point I had a dream and a wish that I could get this, but when I tried it in some expositions and exhibitions, it was very difficult to sit in it. And then that plastic surface was like, it like gave me a sweaty feeling. So no, not nice, not good. And, but it's beautiful, and it's interesting, and the kids surely love it, and on some terrace of a summer cottage it's a most splendid object.

interactions.feelings: And it has been a significant object at celebrations. When there has been an important, important event in the family, and a celebration space, then the Myrnas have been brought into use, and they have like given that celebration its own glory and place of honor.

And this chair by Eero Aarnio. It is charming. It has lovely shapes. And there comes the lights and the colours, and so on. And someone says this is a useless object. I think this is… As I told before here, sailing on the waves of the lake with this one was a lot of fun, also for an adult.

interactions.feelings: And I chose this Jerry canister because there may have been juice, water, and gasoline in it. All of these. And we used to have a boat, and there was water in it then. So when one is on an island or something like that, there may not always be a well there. So it has been used as a water jug then. So that's why I took this Jerry canister. That’s the memory it brought up.
